## First-Principles Decomposition of Phase 0: Context

A world-class context/onboarding phase for software projects must cover these
atomic responsibilities. I catalog them here before comparing against existing skills.

### ATOMIC RESPONSIBILITY INVENTORY

**A. Project Identity & State**
A1. What is the project (mission, purpose, stakeholders)
A2. Current health snapshot (working/broken/degraded)
A3. Current development velocity (fast, slow, blocked)
A4. Business constraints (budget, timeline, compliance)
A5. Stakeholder map (decision makers, users, operators)

**B. Codebase Structure**
B1. File system layout and conventions
B2. Entry points and startup sequences
B3. Module/component dependency graph
B4. Data models and schema understanding
B5. Test inventory and coverage
B6. Build and CI/CD pipeline topology

**C. Architecture Understanding**
C1. Architectural pattern (monolith, microservices, etc.)
C2. Layer topology (presentation, business, data)
C3. Data flow maps for critical paths
C4. External integrations inventory
C5. Event/queue topology
C6. Scaling characteristics

**D. Quality Baseline**
D1. Code quality metrics (complexity, duplication, coverage)
D2. Security posture scan
D3. Dependency health and vulnerability status
D4. Technical debt inventory with priority scoring
D5. Performance baseline (latency, throughput)
D6. Documentation coverage

**E. Historical Context**
E1. Past incident patterns and failure modes
E2. Architectural decision records (what and WHY)
E3. Tribal knowledge and undocumented gotchas
E4. Legacy code boundaries and modernization status
E5. Team knowledge distribution (bus factor)

**F. Infrastructure & Operations**
F1. Deployment topology (environments, regions, cloud)
F2. Monitoring and alerting inventory
F3. Disaster recovery posture (RTO/RPO)
F4. Cost analysis and optimization opportunities
F5. Secret management and IAM posture

**G. Process & Governance**
G1. Team conventions and coding standards
G2. Documentation governance and SSoT structure
G3. Definition of Done and contribution process
G4. Change management and review process
G5. Compliance and regulatory requirements

**H. Knowledge Handoff**
H1. Structured extraction from departing developers
H2. Bus factor analysis and mitigation
H3. Runbook completeness for critical operations
H4. Decision archaeology from git/PR history

**I. New Project Scaffolding (if greenfield)**
I1. Tech stack selection with rationale
I2. Project structure initialization
I3. Baseline tooling (lint, format, test, CI)
I4. Initial security and quality baselines

**J. Research & Discovery (pre-work for brainstorm phase)**
J1. Search before building (existing solutions)
J2. Competitive landscape awareness
J3. Market/domain context
J4. User mental models and existing behavior

