## Finding: Forensic Archaeology Mode Missing from team_knowledge_transfer

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: team_knowledge_transfer's step 3 (Decision Archaeology) via git blame is the only mechanism for extracting knowledge when the original developer has ALREADY LEFT. But the skill is structured as "do this during the handoff period" — implying the developer is present. When inheriting a project with no handoff (departed team, acquired company, abandoned open source project), the structured interview (step 2) and shadow sessions (step 5) are impossible. The skill needs a "Dead Team Archaeology" mode that relies entirely on: git history forensics, issue tracker analysis, PR description archaeology, commit message analysis, and documentation recovery. Currently, only step 3 partially addresses this.
### Proposed Resolution: Add a "Forensic Mode" variant to team_knowledge_transfer. Trigger: "The original team is gone", "No one to interview", "Inherited with no handoff". Process: (1) Git forensics (blame, log, bisect), (2) Issue tracker archaeology, (3) PR description mining, (4) Slack/email archive search (if accessible), (5) External artifact search (blog posts, conference talks, Stack Overflow answers by team members). Output: reconstructed decision log and tribal knowledge document.
### Cross-Phase Impact: This is the most common real-world scenario for "joining an existing project" and the current skill handles it poorly.

